      <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_ Princeton_1800-01_page01.jpg"/>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <date when="1800-01-27"/>January 27, 18XX. </dateline>
               <salute>
                  Dear Sir,
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               27 Jan<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>. <unclear>18??</unclear>
               Dear Sir<lb/>
               I have just received yours<lb/>
               of the 20<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. <choice><orig>inst</orig><reg>instant</reg></choice> - I am sorry<lb/>
               that the battery goes on so slowly<lb/>
               - my having followed this <choice><orig>parsi<lb/>
               -monious</orig><reg>parsimonious</reg></choice> plan has cost us both<lb/>
               much trouble - At <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Bristol_ENK">Bristol</placeName> it<lb/>
               plagued me more than I chose<lb/>
               to complain of -<lb/></p>
            <p>I know that I could have all<lb/>
               the types that are immediately<lb/>
               wanting for £5 &amp; I<lb/>
               think if I can find a moments<lb/>
               <unclear>languor???</unclear> &amp; next week when I go<lb/>
               to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> to attend <unclear>Castl<hi rend="superscript">l</hi></unclear> that<lb/>
               I can have them cast &amp; sent<lb/>
               to you to print <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early1">Harry &amp; Lucy<lb/>
               &amp; Frank</title><lb/></p>
            <p>Observe - Take Notice - NB -<lb/>
               <figure><figDesc>Pen-drawn illustration of a manicule stressing the next words.</figDesc></figure>I never said that I thought<lb/>

<pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_ Princeton_1800-01_page02.jpg"/>

               Papas &amp; Mamas would be at<lb/>
               the trouble to learn to teach I <choice><orig>al-<lb/>
               ways</orig><reg>always</reg></choice> feared they would not &amp;<lb/>
               therefore I refused to be paid for<lb/>
               the Book till it had actually<lb/>
               succeeded - But I did &amp; do say<lb/>
               that it is an excellent <choice><orig>improve<lb/>
               -ment</orig><reg>improvement</reg></choice> in the art of teaching to read<lb/>
               though I say it that <choice><orig>sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi></orig><reg>should</reg></choice> not say it.<lb/></p>
            <p>I feel so many qualms about<lb/>
               mixing new &amp; old in the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Paren1">Parents<lb/>
               Assistant</title> that I must beg - nay<lb/>
               insist that all the old <unclear>may??</unclear><lb/>
               <add>without any mixing of new</add><lb/>
               finish in the month <unclear></unclear> March<lb/>
               <add>if you can put them all in March -</add><lb/>
               <add>or <unclear></unclear> <unclear>fact</unclear> of volumes if they will fill them</add><lb/>
               if the Barney <unclear></unclear> is known<lb/>
               <unclear>aside</unclear> we dont care - but we are<lb/>
               convinced that the Public <unclear>&amp;c.</unclear> will<lb/>
               be better pleased to have a<lb/>
               new series<lb/></p>
            <p><title ref="./Workography.xml#Moral1">Moral Tales</title> being a new series<lb/>
               of the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Paren1">Parents Assistant</title><lb/>
               by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss E &amp;c.</persName> —<lb/></p>
            <p>She has lately written two or<lb/>

<pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_ Princeton_1800-01_page03.jpg"/>

               three beautiful things - some of<lb/>
               them dramatic for <del>Children</del> <add>young people</add><lb/>
               One that I almost prefer to<lb/>
               Lazy Lawrence - If you are<lb/>
               good, &amp; tractable about the arrange<lb/>
               -ment above mentioned you shall<lb/>
               have them!!! —<lb/></p>
            <p>I understand that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> is to<lb/>
               offer you a translation of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BerqA1">Berquins</persName><lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Bibli1"><foreign>Bibliotheque de village</foreign></title> — the<lb/>
               original is excellent &amp; I know that<lb/>
               the translators are fully equal to a<lb/>
               far more arduous task —<lb/></p>
            <p>When you write please to<lb/>
               make your clerk send an account<lb/>
               of the Books sent to us since we<lb/>
               left <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> - for <add>all</add> your accounts have<lb/>
               not reached us &amp; we do not know<lb/>
               what Books we ought to have —<lb/>
               - <choice><orig>N<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>.</orig><reg>Number</reg></choice> 3 of one of the sets of Anderson is<lb/>
               wanting - please to put it<lb/>
               in your memorandum book -<lb/></p>
            <p><del>Please to send us to M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DugdX1">Dugdale</persName> bookseller></del><lb/>
               We <hi rend="underline">desire</hi> to have the <choice><orig>vol</orig><reg>volume</reg></choice> of the<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Bibli2"><foreign>Bibliotheque Brittanique</foreign></title> which<lb/>
               translates part of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Pract1"><choice><orig>Prac Ed</orig><reg>Practical Education</reg></choice></title> — we<lb/>
               want to correct our stile by seeing<lb/>
               its crookedness reflected in another language<lb/></p>
            <closer>
               <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_ Princeton_1800-01_page04.jpg"/>
               <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> wrote to us to say that he thought<lb/>
                  <title ref="./Workography.xml#Rivul1"><hi rend="underline">Rivuletta</hi></title> should not be thrown away<lb/>
                  upon <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early1"><hi rend="underline">Early Lessons</hi></title> that it should be kept<lb/>
                  for a new Edition of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Pract1"><choice><orig>Prac Ed</orig><reg>Practical Education</reg></choice></title> - We agree with<lb/>
                  him in this opinion &amp; request you will<lb/>
                  take out of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early1"><hi rend="underline">Rosamond</hi></title> the few pages which<lb/>
                  <hi rend="underline">relate</hi> to it - they will leave no Hiatus —<lb/></p>
                  <p>We shall send for books in future by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DugdX1">Dugdale</persName><lb/></p>
                  <p>Copy to Johnson<lb/>
                     Jan<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1800<lb/></p>
            </postscript>
            <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
            <!-- Format for postscripts. 
               Postscripts do NOT go inside closer tags. Adjust to take into account the order in your letter. 
               Sometimes the signature is on page three, the address on page four, then the postscript follows back on the top of page one, for example.-->
